 which sex a person should belong? This groundbreaking analysis of clinical case histories shows how sex changed from an outward appearance inscribed in a social body to something to be found deep inside body and self. A fascinating, easy to follow, yet sophisticated argument addressing major issues of the history of body, sex, and self, this volume will fit advanced undergraduate courses, while challenging specialists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGender identityxHistory. 0aGender identity. 0aIntersexualityxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex rolexHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aanatomy.  agender identity.  agender.  agenitals.  ainner self.  along nineteenth century.  asex.  asexuality.  asocial body.1 aMak, Geertje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779429140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847794291423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847794291/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles